{"type":"message","id":"d292ee0e","parentId":"a5c2441e","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:10:48.990Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_p0w2n2mmhk6f_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"      status: servicesMap.supabase.status === 'ok' ? 'connected' : 'disconnected',\r\n      pool_size: 20,\r\n      active_connections: servicesMap.supabase.status === 'ok' ? 5 : 0,\r\n    },\r\n    memory,\r\n    redis: {\r\n      status: 'disconnected', // Redis not currently used in compose\r\n    }\r\n  };\r\n\r\n  res.status(status === 'down' ? 503 : 200).json(body);\r\n}\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776031848928}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f443944","parentId":"d292ee0e","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:10:51.615Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The health check just hard-codes `status: 'disconnected'` for Redis. It doesn't actually check if Redis is connected. This is a known issue - it's not really checking Redis status, just returning a hardcoded value.\n\nNow I need to check if the redis service is actually connecting properly. Let me check the redis config file.","thinkingSignature":"3a00e1e8d4f9915b529978b83271bb8753c9d10dfdcca8ac51b2b59207ec39bc"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_nb49umnp5eiw_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/backend/src/config/redis.ts"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":184,"output":111,"cacheRead":90432,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":90727,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776031848994,"responseId":"062b4b6913b24936205f406c6b216050"}}
{"type":"message","id":"b8e1e789","parentId":"1f443944","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:10:51.858Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_nb49umnp5eiw_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"import Redis from 'ioredis';\nimport dotenv from 'dotenv';\ndotenv.config();\n\nconst redisUrl = process.env.REDIS_URL || 'redis://localhost:6379';\n\nclass RedisService {\n  private static instance: Redis | null = null;\n\n  public static getInstance(): Redis {\n    if (!this.instance) {\n      this.instance = new Redis(redisUrl, {\n        maxRetriesPerRequest: 1,\n        retryStrategy: (times) => {\n          // Desactivar reintentos infinitos si falla para no bloquear el proceso\n          if (times > 3) return null;\n          return Math.min(times * 50, 2000);\n        },\n        // Silenciar errores de conexión\n        lazyConnect: true\n      });\n\n      let lastLoggedError = 0;\n      this.instance.on('error', (err) => {\n        // En desarrollo, solo logueamos una advertencia una vez cada 30 segundos\n        // para no saturar la consola si el desarrollador no tiene Redis.\n        const now = Date.now();\n        if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development') {\n          if (now - lastLoggedError > 30000) {\n            console.warn('[Redis] No disponible localmente (Modo Desarrollo). Algunas funciones de cola podrían estar pausadas.');\n            lastLoggedError = now;\n          }\n        } else {\n          console.error('[Redis] Error de conexión:', err.message);\n        }\n      });\n    }\n    return this.instance;\n  }\n}\n\nexport const redis = RedisService.getInstance();\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776031851794}}
{"type":"message","id":"016ca61e","parentId":"b8e1e789","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:10:55.716Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Redis configuration uses `lazyConnect: true`, which means Redis doesn't automatically connect when the module loads. It needs to be called explicitly. But ioredis should automatically try to connect when you perform an operation.\n\nLet me check if the Redis connection is actually being established by looking at the logs more carefully or by adding a quick test. Let me also check if the health check actually tests the Redis connection or just returns a static \"disconnected\" status.\n\nLooking at the health controller, it seems like the status is hardcoded to 'disconnected'. The health service doesn't actually test if Redis is connected - it just reports it as disconnected.\n\nBut the actual issue is: **the dashboard doesn't load because Redis is not being used for session management**. Even if Redis was connected, I need to verify if sessions are actually stored in Redis.\n\nLet me check the auth service to see where sessions are stored:\n","thinkingSignature":"457e6cfe2d98dbf49475ea464a8a6bd192a310e97e0f769991ce3da57169e59e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_sukq3pay2mp3_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -rn \"session\\|cookie\\|token\" /home/travis/Lookitry/Lookitry/backend/src/services/auth.service.ts | head -30"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":397,"output":238,"cacheRead":90592,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":91227,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776031851862,"responseId":"062b4b6c8191fada7cd6bfbfa7b0cbed"}}
